I recently had the privilege of visiting a beautiful mosque in my community, and I must say it was an awe-inspiring experience that left a profound impact on me. As someone who appreciates the diverse cultures and religious traditions that enrich our world, I was deeply moved by the ambiance, architectural grandeur, and the overall spiritual atmosphere of this remarkable place of worship.

From the moment I stepped inside, I was immediately struck by the serene and tranquil environment. The mosque's architectural design was nothing short of breathtaking, with intricate patterns and elegant calligraphy adorning the walls and ceilings. The interplay of light and shadow created a mesmerizing effect, further enhancing the ambiance of the prayer hall.

The mosque was meticulously maintained, reflecting the devotion and care of the community that worships there. The cleanliness and orderliness of the premises were truly commendable, creating an inviting space for visitors and worshippers alike. It was evident that great effort had been put into maintaining the mosque as a sacred sanctuary for spiritual contemplation.

What impressed me the most was the warm and inclusive atmosphere fostered within the mosque. Despite being from a different religious background, I was welcomed with open arms by the friendly and hospitable staff and fellow worshippers. They were more than willing to answer any questions I had and engage in meaningful conversations about their faith and the mosque's role within the community.

Despite being from a different religious background, I was welcomed with open arms by the friendly and hospitable staff and fellow worshippers. They were more than willing to answer any questions I had and engage in meaningful conversations about their faith and the mosque's role within the community.

featured_reviews.review_id:
It was built by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahanbetween 1644 and 1656 at a cost of 1 million rupees, and was inaugurated by an Imam from Bukhara, present-day Uzbekistan. The mosque was completed in 1656 AD with three great gates, four towers and two 40 metres high minaretsconstructed with strips of red sandstone and white marble. The courtyard can accommodate more than 25,000 people. There are three domes on the terrace which are surrounded by the two minarets. On the floor, a total of 899 black borders are marked for worshippers. The architectural plan of Badshahi Masjid, built by Shah Jahan's son Aurangzeb at Lahore, Pakistan, is similar to the Jama Masjid.

HistoryEdit

Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan built the Jama Masjid between 1644 and 1656. It was constructed by more than 5000 workers. It was originally called Masjid-i-Jahan Numa, meaning 'mosque commanding view of the world'. The construction was done under the supervision of Saadullah Khan, wazir (or prime minister) during Shah Jahan's reign. The cost of the construction at the time was one million Rupees.[1] Shah Jahan also built the Taj Mahal, at Agra and the Red Fortin New Delhi, which stands opposite the Jama Masjid.

The Jama Masjid was completed in 1656 AD (1066 AH).[1] The mosque was inaugurated by an Imam Bukhari, a mullah from Bukhara, Uzbekistan, on 23 July 1656, on the invitation from Shah Jahan.[2]About 25,000 people can pray in the courtyard at a time .[3][4] The mosque is commonly called "Jama" which means Friday.[1]

After the British victory in the Revolt of 1857, they confiscated the mosque and stationed their soldiers there. They also wanted to destroy the mosque as an act of punishment to the city. But due to opposition faced, the demolition was not done.[5]

The iconic mosque is one of the last monuments built under Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan. After the construction of the monument in 1656, it remained the royal mosque of the emperors until the end of the Mughal period.

During 1948, the last Nizam of Hyderabad, Asaf Jah VII was asked for a donation of Rs75,000 to repair one-fourth of the mosque floor. The Nizam instead sanctioned Rs3 lakh, stating that the remaining three-fourths of the mosque should not look old.

I have been visiting this mosque regularly to offer my prayers, and I have to say that it is one of the best places to connect with Allah and feel a sense of peace and tranquility. The mosque is a clean, simple, and well-maintained space, with a peaceful atmosphere that is conducive to prayer and reflection.

I appreciate the community of worshippers at the mosque who are always friendly, welcoming, and supportive. Everyone is united in their purpose of offering prayers and seeking Allah's blessings, which creates a sense of brotherhood and sisterhood among the worshippers.

The imam's sermons are always insightful and thought-provoking, providing guidance and inspiration to the worshippers. I also appreciate the mosque's effort in organizing special prayers during the month of Ramadan, including iftar and taraweeh prayers, which allow the community to come together and break their fasts in a peaceful and spiritual environment.

Overall, I highly recommend this mosque to anyone looking for a simple and supportive place to connect with Allah through prayer. Whether you are a regular worshipper or simply looking to learn more about Islam, this mosque offers a welcoming and peaceful environment that is sure to enrich your spiritual journey.
